{"key":"post-12344955","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12344955</id>\n<content>Water will not exist in a liquid state at 300F.&amp;nbsp; It will turn to steam at 212F.&amp;nbsp; If you continue to heat it, it will attempt to pressurize if in a sealed container.&amp;nbsp; Since there's holes and a filter in pf jars, it can't pressurize and the path of least resistance is out through those holes.&amp;nbsp; It has nothing to do with the amount the water will expand, because there will be no water at 300F.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A quick search here will reveal that it's almost a rite of passage for new growers to want to figure out a way to avoid steam sterilization for some reason.&amp;nbsp; There's been hundreds before you. . .who now own large kettles and/or pressure cookers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;An Errant Egret said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After all, my current jars are only showing growth which has doubled in the last 24 hours, &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A indication of mold.&amp;nbsp; Mushroom mycelium doesn't normally grow that fast.&amp;nbsp; Pictures would help ID.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12344994</next>\n<prev>12344923</prev>\n<first>12303766</first>\n<last>17239315</last>\n<when>1270607424</when>\n<utime>04/07/10 05:30 AM</utime>\n</post>"}